    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "999a789f_0eee361e",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 204,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-05T00:45:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We\u0027d need to call NextNote or move the GetNoteSegment loop into ReadNote since we might need to retry into the next segment. I tried it out, but it doesn\u0027t get tail-call optimized because of the local strings\u0027 destructors.\n\nIt would be nice to get rid of kRetry/InternalResult, though. What do you think of using a retry_ member?",
      "parentUuid": "36dc6ddb_246bf5a6",
      "revId": "772202373065cc8d86fccb8240edc90c3a73c1d9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "dc0a6d21_61d90ce3",
        "filename": "snapshot/elf/elf_image_reader.cc",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 281,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-12-04T21:43:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This (and all other reads in this method) should be serviced by a subrange reader that makes sure you don’t go out of the segment’s bounds.\n\nIt may make the most sense to set up the subrange reader in NextNote() when you advance to a new PT_NOTE segment. This ProcessMemoryRange could also be used in place of segment_end_address_.\n\nUsing the subrange reader would allow you to get rid of the custom overflow detection in this method: you could just let Read() fail, log something for you, and all you’d have to do is return kError (which you’re already doing anyway).",
      "revId": "772202373065cc8d86fccb8240edc90c3a73c1d9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
